Generated with `-hq -ts -cache` flags.
Successfully compiled, but the inference never finished when run `./lm_fpga.elf input.npy output.npy `

Oh! Sorry for the delay.
It is a hardware restriction. There is a counter with 10 bits that prevents counting channels beyond 1024. And this network seems to use more than 1024 channels.

But is possible to synthesize another IP with higher limit, like 4096 or 8192. That should solve the problem.

issue.title: Need documentation for the limitation of DLK

repository.name: blueoil
repository.description: Bring Deep Learning to small devices

issue.body:
Currently, there is no documentation for the limitation of DLK. I think it is important to document what operations and parameters DLK can / cannot support. This can really help users/developers in designing the network and save a lot of time for debugging.

From what I know, currently DLK has the following limitations:
- No support for conv2d with kernel size not equal to 3x3 
- No support for conv2d_transpose
- No support for concat of mixed data types (e.g., quantized values and float values)
- No support for space to depth if the output depth is not a multiple of 32
- No support for depth to space if the input depth is not a multiple of 128

Thank you!

body:
@antonionevado 
When I changed max conv channel under 1024, the problem comes still.
Could you have any idea?

pb and input, output npy is here.
https://github.com/blue-oil/blueoil/tree/59de07d12f83437553b3866ffe96d19eceae9b26/dlk/examples/segmentation/lm_bisenet_quantize_camvid

@ruimashita 
About the error in x86 I'm not sure why doesn't match, it could be that the tolerance for comparing the expected values and the real values is too low. Or could be related to a precision problem related to the thresholds. Please, try to run on x86 with and without the `-ts` option.

About the version for FPGA, I checked the model and the second convolution (which is quantized) seems to use 1x1x2048 kernels. If that is the case, then we can follow the restriction of less than 1024 channels or increase the number of bits of the counter in IPv2. 
Do you want us to set up a higher limit for number of channels?

@antonionevado 
Thanks !!!

> the second convolution (which is quantized) seems to use 1x1x2048 kernels

I overlooked this convolution, I will re-think about network architecture to reduce channel size under 1024.
